Vincent Van Gogh


Vincent Van Gogh
================


About Vincent Van Gogh
----------------------
Vincent Van Gogh was a Dutch post-impressionist painter who is among the most famous and influential figures in the history of Western art. He created more than 2,100 artworks, including around 860 oil paintings, most of which date from the last two years of his life.


Timeline
--------
* 1853: Vincent Van Gogh was born in Groot-Zundert, Netherlands.
* 1869: He left school and started working at Goupil & Cie, an art dealership in The Hague.
* 1873: He was transferred to London to work at the firm's branch there.
* 1876: He was fired from Goupil & Cie and decided to become a full-time artist.
* 1886: He moved to Paris and met other famous artists, including Paul Gauguin and Henri de Toulouse-Lautrec.
* 1888: He moved to Arles, in the south of France, where he created some of his most famous works, such as "Sunflowers" and "The Night Cafe".
* 1889: He was voluntarily admitted to a mental asylum in Saint-Paul-de-Mausole, where he continued to paint.
* 1890: He died of a self-inflicted gunshot wound at the age of 37.


Gallery
-------
![The Potato Eaters](https://www.vangoghmuseum.nl/-/media/images/collection/the-potato-eaters-1885/vgm-photography-jan-kees-steenman/the-potato-eaters-1885-jan-kees-steenman.jpg)
### The Potato Eaters
1885

![Sunflowers](https://www.vangoghmuseum.nl/-/media/images/collection/sunflowers-1889/vgm-photography-jan-kees-steenman/sunflowers-1889-jan-kees-steenman.jpg)
### Sunflowers
1889

![The Starry Night](https://www.vangoghmuseum.nl/-/media/images/collection/starry-night-1889/vgm-photography-jan-kees-steenman/starry-night-1889-jan-kees-steenman.jpg)
### The Starry Night
1889

![Almond Blossom](https://www.vangoghmuseum.nl/-/media/images/collection/almond-blossom-1890/vgm-photography-jan-kees-steenman/almond-blossom-1890-jan-kees-steenman.jpg)
### Almond Blossom
1890

Legacy
------
Vincent Van Gogh's influence on art has been immense. His bold use of color and expressive brushwork paved the way for the development of modern art. His tragic life and early death also contributed to his enduring popularity and mystique.


